Mr Giteme is charged with giving false information to a person employed in the public service contrary to section 129 (a) of the Penal Code. 











Joseph Giteme.
Photo credit: Charles Wanyoro | Nation Media Group

 

Mr Mbogo was shot in the same week the case was revived after having been terminated in 2016 by a Director of Public Prosecutions officer. 

Other witnesses had developed cold feet after Mr Mbogo was shot and injured. 

Mr Miriti, 31, is Giteme’s step-brother, while Mr Kalung’e, 58, is his wife Purity Makena’s uncle. 

But before they made the trip, they received a call ostensibly from Shimo la Tewa that they were being held there awaiting arraignment for an unspecified crime. 

The caller, who identified himself as a remand prisoner from Meru, claimed that the three appeared to have been beaten up, and appeared to be in bad shape. 






Charles Kalung'e.
Photo credit: Charles Wanyoro | Nation Media Group

 

The man said he was being held at the maximum-security facility after he allegedly caused a fatal vehicular homicide and had made contact with the three after realising they were from Meru. 



