However, Kanuni MCA Josephat Mugambi, who received the call in presence of the family members, said an independent scrutiny indicated that the call may have been placed from within Maua town. 

“The call came as residents had asked me that we hold a demonstration over the abduction. He said he saw them as they took fingerprints and were about to be taken to the police station. We reported the incident at Maua police station but they have not given us any feedback many hours later,” he said. 

Demonstrations held 

Mr Mugambi later joined hundreds of residents who clashed with police as they held demonstrations over the disappearance of the three men. 

Police were forced to fire tear gas canisters as they were overwhelmed by the mob that pelted them with stones in Antubochiu area. 

The group had walked for over 10 kilometres to the Modern area of Maua town intending to storm the local police station but turned back on being informed that their demonstration was illegal. 

The MCA, together with Ms Makena said Mr Giteme, had reported to the police that he was being trailed by people who claimed to be police officers, a day before he went missing. 



